{
  "expertRole": "Pre-mortem Analyst",
  "score": 88,
  "verdict": "needs-revision",
  "findings": [
    "Silent re-break via model drift (top failure narrative): the fix is prompt-only and the regression guard tests the SKILL.md prescriptions, not emitted output. Six months out, a model update or a new CHECK-code family pattern-matches the uppercase display text and emits `#CHECK-...` fragments again; broken anchors fail silently (page loads at top, link still looks valid), so nobody notices until another consumer files a bug like fortune-os #120. Early warning sign: fragment casing in freshly posted review bodies. Mitigation: deterministic lowercasing in the TS emit path — the code already parses `[CHECK-…](…)` in stripReviewChrome (.github/actions/code-review-action/src/reviewOutput/inlineCommentBody.ts), so normalizing the fragment there is cheap — plus a lowercase-fragment item in the pr:review self-check list. The plan's 'No TypeScript runtime change' is a design choice that leaves this open.",
    "Guard scope is pinned and the existing safety net masks the class: the new test covers exactly three SKILL.md files, and the plan itself notes linkResolution.test.ts indexes anchors 'in both original and lowercased form' — meaning it passes either casing and will never catch a recurrence in a new skill (pr:monitor evolving past delegation, a future pr:* skill, a docs chapter adopting the pattern). Failure narrative: a fourth file prescribes the link form next quarter, uppercase, green CI. Mitigation: glob all claude-plugins/**/SKILL.md in the guard, and tighten linkResolution's explicit-anchor fragment matching to lowercase-only so the whole class is caught structurally.",
    "Convention-divergence risk with RFC-0001 and the synced canonical block is dismissed in one unverified line: 'RFC-0001's anchor clause covers heading anchors and remains accurate' has no verify step, and the canonical reference-formatting block is byte-identical across ~24 files with a sync guard. If any of those prescribe or imply 'fragment matches the anchor id', a future author re-derives the uppercase form from the canonical source and the guard files diverge from the convention doc. Mitigation: add an explicit verify step (grep rfc/0001 and the canonical block for anchor-fragment wording) and bump the in-place RFC version if the lowercase rule belongs there.",
